ce:section.ce:para:
To construct LED, the D-CDs powder was directly mixed with AB epoxy silicone resin, and the mixture was coated on a 365 nm excitation GaN LED chips. The emission spectra of the LEDs sample 1–4 constructed with different mass ratio of the D-CDs powder and resin (5%, 10%, 15% and 20%) are depicted in Fig. 4
                        A. Although varied in mass ratio, the emission wavelength of the LEDs samples remained almost fixed. However, the mass ratio greatly affected the luminance of LED samples. As the mass ratio increased, the luminance of the LED increased from 1726 cd m−2 to 3922 cd m−2. However, mass ratio beyond 15% led to a decline in luminance. The corresponding digital images and CIE chromaticity diagram of the LED samples in Fig. 4B visually depicts the blue light of the LED. The blue light of the LEDs is hardly affected by the mass ratio, with CIE coordinate and color rendering indices (CRI) values show a slight change from (0.15, 0.13) to (0.18, 0.18) and 34 to 39, respectively (Table 3
                        ). Stable luminous properties are attributed to the stable fluorescence properties of the D-CDs.

Based on these observations, the LED was fabricated with a mass ratio of 15% and an operating voltage of 3.6. The LED exhibits bright blue light with a broad emission band at 432 nm, a CIE coordinate at (0.17, 0.14), a CCT >100000 K and a color rendering index value of 37. The LED shows an efficient conversion of ultraviolet light to visible light with a RGB proportion of 73.8% (Fig. 4D) and the emission intensity of the LED constructed by the D-CDs powder still maintains 81.8% of the initial value after 4 months of daylight storage (Fig. 5
                        ). Compared with the LED reported in the literature (Table 5
                        ), the as-prepared LED not only achieves a comparable luminance of 3922 K but also with the advantages of low cast, low toxicity and easy fabrication.
